c.

The stacked rose diagram is fairly hard to interpret, as it is difficult to see the distributions of airline and airline sentiment in the plot. The marginal distribution of airline is mapped on to the radius of each of the circle sectors. The conditional distribution of tweet sentiment given that the tweet was about Delta Airlines is mapped to the radii of the sections of the circle sector labeled “Delta” as separated by color. It seems that United had the most tweets, while Virigin America had by far the least. US Airways and American Airlines had similar counts, as well as Delta and Southwest. With respect to Delta Airlines, about half of the tweets have negative sentiments, while only a small percentage of tweets are positive.

This is an absolutely terrible graph for mutiple reasons. It is difficult to compare the counts of categories that are not next to each other, since it is harder to compare radii than heights. It is hard to decipher the absolute counts of each category, since the labels on the y-axis don’t correspond to the axis lines on the graph. Also, the graph distorts the data, since the area is proportional to the counts squared.

  1. Often, with large datasets, it can take a small amount of time to do the calculations necessary to create the bar chart. This is because when you call geom_bar(), it tabulates the counts in each category when the line of code is run. For large datasets, it’s better to store the counts ahead of time and then reference these when creating the bar chart, as we did in Lab 03 with gender_marginal. Here, create a bar plot showing the distribution of day_of_week (at the count scale), but calculate the marginal distribution ahead of time (i.e., use an approach similar to Lab 03 Problem 1).

  1. Another way to visualize two categorical variables is with a “side-by-side” bar chart. To do this, use the following code:
day_15 <- bike_data %>%

# Using full bike_data

  1. Another way to visualize two categorical variables is with a “proportional” bar chart. To do this, use the same code as above, except change position = "dodge" (which will place the bars side-by-side) to position = "fill" which will fix the heights of the bars to all be 1, and fill them in proportionally according to the second variable. Be sure to change your y-axis label to something appropriate.
proportion <- ggplot(day_15, aes(x = day_of_week, y = count, fill = less_than_15_mins)) + 
 geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "fill") +

      title = "Day of Week Counts Short and Longer Rides") +
 scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Less than 15 Mins"))

  1. Compare the graphs you created in (e), (f), and (g) – that is, compare the stacked, side-by-side, and proportional bar charts.

Solution: The 3 graphs in (e),(f),(g) visualize the same data in different ways.

The stacked bar chart (e) provides us with information of the total number of riders per day which is easily to compare, additionally the first category (in this case “Less that 15 minutes”) can also be compared across the days. It is harder to look at the proportional splits of the length of rides per day and the variations of rides over 15 minutes in length.

The side-by-side bar chart (f) gives use the ability to look at all the subgroups (length of ride > 15 minutes and < 15 minutes) and look at the changes in these subpopulations over the days. Using this plot it is harder to compare total number of riders across days and the proportion of types of riders for a given day.

The proportional bar chart (g) gives us the ability to examine the proportions/mixtures of the subgroups (length of ride > 15 minutes and < 15 minutes), it doesn’t present counts per day of subgroups or total number of riders per day.

Depending upon what you’d like to show, any of these 3 plots could be optimal, just need to select the one that gives you the best visual of the information you are looking for.

  1. There are even more ways to show bar charts at the proportion or percentage scales. In the background, the geom_bar() function calculates the counts in each category, which are stored in an object called ..count... Using the default settings (i.e. just geom_bar()), the y-axis aesthetic is automatically assigned to the ..count.. object (i.e., geom_bar(aes(y = ..count..)) will give you the same result as geom_bar()). We can use this to create bar charts at the proportion scale in another way:
  • Start by creating the bar chart in the standard way, using bike_data and not the pre-calculated marginal distribution.
  • To do this, scale the y-axis aesthetic by the sum of the counts, i.e.: ... + geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..))).
  • Be sure to use properly labeled axes, titles, etc.
ggplot(bike_data,aes(x= day_of_week,fill = day_of_week)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y=(..count..)/sum(..count..))) +
  labs(x = "Day of Week", y = "Proportion of total",
      title = "Day of Week Counts Short and Longer Rides") +
 scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Less than 15 Mins"))

  1. Convert this to the percentage scale by multiplying the y-axis aesthetic from (k) by 100. Be sure to use properly labeled axes, titles, etc.
ggplot(bike_data,aes(x= day_of_week,fill = day_of_week)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y=100*((..count..)/sum(..count..)))) +
  labs(x = "Day of Week", y = "Percentage of total (%)",
      title = "Day of Week Counts Short and Longer Rides") +
 scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Less than 15 Mins"))

Reordering Categories and Bars

a.

The default for factors in R is to order them alphabetically.

b.

# install.packages('forcats')
library(forcats)

The fct_recode function can rename the categories. The function fct_inorder reorders the categories in order of first appearance. The function fct_infreq reorders the categories by frequency. A combination of the functions fct_rev and fct_infreq can reorder the categories by reverse order of frequency.

g.

The bar graph shows the distribution of the duration of bike rides, categorized by whether they were longer or shorter than 15 minutes, conditional on the day of week of the bike ride. The day of week is shown on the x-axis, and the number of bike rides on each day of the week is shown on the y-axis. The fill of each bar is separated by the number of rides on each day of the week that were longer or shorter than 15 minutes. The plot seems to show that the proportion of the number of bike rides that were less than 15 minutes compared to the total number of bike rides is largest for Wednesday and Thursday. In general, the proportion of rides that were less than 15 minutes was smallest during the weekend days, as can be seen from the larger proportion of red, representing the bike rides 15 minutes or longer, in the bars for the weekends compared to the bars of the other days. Overall, based on the heights of the bars, weekends seem to have more overall rides per day compared to the weekdays.

Problem 6

(3 points each)

Incorporating Statistical Information Into Graphs

a.

# airline_tweets <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sventura/315-code-and-datasets/master/data/Tweets.csv")

#  Add the following information to the airline_counts dataset:
#    Proportions and percentages corresponding to each category
#    The standard error on the proportios or percentages corresponding to each category
#    Lower bound of an (approximate) 95% confidence interval around the true proportion in each category
#    Upper bound of an (approximate) 95% confidence interval around the true proportion in each category

#  Manipulate the airline 
airline_counts <- airline_tweets %>%  #  Start with the airline_tweets data.frame
  group_by(airline) %>%  #  group by the airline variable
  summarise(count = n()) %>%  #  summarize the dataset by calculating the count of each airline
  mutate(total = sum(count),  #  add total number of observations
         proportion = count / total,  #  add proportions
         percentage = proportion * 100,  #  add percentages
         std_error = sqrt(proportion * (1-proportion) / total),  #  add standard error of each proportion
         lower = proportion - 1.96 * std_error,  #  compute lower bound
         upper = proportion + 1.96 * std_error)  #  compute upper bound

airline_counts

The difference between these two graphs is the scale of the y-axis distribution: one is a proportion out of 1, and the other is a percentage out of 100.

c.

ggplot(data = airline_counts) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = airline, y = proportion), stat = "identity") + 
  labs(x = "Airline", y = "Proportion of Tweets", 
       title = "Distribution of Tweets by Airline Mentioned", 
       caption = "Twitter Airline Sentiment dataset",
       subtitle = "With Added Standard Error Bars") + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(x = airline, ymin = lower, ymax = upper))

d.

The proportions of tweets mentioning American Airlines and US Airways are not statistically significantly different. The error bars on the graph intercept, meaning that the 95% confidence intervals intersect. Thus, we do not have any evidence that the two proportions are different.
